1
00:03:21,510 --> 00:03:25,100
An article, which I believe appeared
in a newspaper, asked why,

2
00:03:25,310 --> 00:03:29,610
since it would seem that you are
in effect the Mayor of Chicago,

3
00:03:29,810 --> 00:03:34,320
you're not simply being
appointed to that position.

4
00:03:37,360 --> 00:03:41,870
Well, I tell ya, it's touching.
Like a lot of things in life,

5
00:03:42,080 --> 00:03:46,410
we laugh because it's funny,
and we laugh because it's true.

6
00:03:46,620 --> 00:03:48,580
Some people say,
reformers here say:

7
00:03:48,790 --> 00:03:52,750
"Put that man in jail,
what does he think he is doing?"

8
00:03:52,960 --> 00:03:56,420
What I hope I'm doing, and here's
where your paper's got a point,

9
00:03:56,630 --> 00:03:58,930
is I'm responding to
the will of the people.

10
00:04:01,890 --> 00:04:06,480
People are gonna drink. We all
know that. All I do is act on that.

11
00:04:06,690 --> 00:04:09,480
And all this talk of bootlegging.
What is bootlegging?

12
00:04:09,690 --> 00:04:13,480
On the boat it's bootlegging,
on Lake Shore Drive it's hospitality.

13
00:04:13,690 --> 00:04:15,940
I'm a businessman.

14
00:04:17,490 --> 00:04:21,160
Your reputation is that you control
your business through violence.

15
00:04:21,370 --> 00:04:26,000
That those that don't purchase your
product are dealt with violently.

16
00:04:31,460 --> 00:04:33,500
It's all right.

17
00:04:34,960 --> 00:04:36,880
I grew up in a tough neighbourhood.

18
00:04:37,090 --> 00:04:39,930
We used to say, "Y ou can get further
with a kind word and a gun"

19
00:04:40,140 --> 00:04:43,220
"than you can
with just a kind word."

20
00:04:44,560 --> 00:04:46,810
And in that neighbourhood
it might've been true.

21
00:04:47,020 --> 00:04:50,600
And sometimes
your reputation follows you.

22
00:04:51,980 --> 00:04:54,770
There is violence in Chicago,
but not by me

23
00:04:54,980 --> 00:04:59,280
and not by anybody I employ.
Because it's not good business.

24
00:05:30,270 --> 00:05:34,770
<i>Leave us alone down here,
we've got everything we need.</i>

25
00:05:34,980 --> 00:05:37,980
The green beer you're peddlin'
ain't any good.

26
00:05:38,190 --> 00:05:42,410
It's not supposed to be good.
It's supposed to be bought.

27
00:05:43,570 --> 00:05:46,330
I'm not buyin' any.

28
00:05:48,410 --> 00:05:52,370
Don't worry about it, Pops,
we won't come back.

29
00:05:55,460 --> 00:05:58,420
- How's everyone at your house today?
- They're fine.

30
00:05:58,630 --> 00:06:02,680
- Is your Mama well?
- She has a little cold.

31
00:06:02,880 --> 00:06:05,100
Oh, she does?

32
00:06:06,260 --> 00:06:09,470
- I'm sorry to hear that.
- But she'll be all right.

33
00:06:15,310 --> 00:06:17,070
- There you go.
- Thank you.

34
00:06:17,270 --> 00:06:22,570
That's all right, sweetie.
You be careful crossin' the street.

35
00:06:22,780 --> 00:06:25,200
- Mister!
- You tell your Mama that...

36
00:06:25,410 --> 00:06:27,950
Hey, Mister! Wait!

37
00:06:28,160 --> 00:06:31,540
Mister! Wait!
You forgot your brief...

38
00:07:36,850 --> 00:07:41,270
Yes, I heard it on the radio.

39
00:07:41,480 --> 00:07:43,860
I know.

40
00:07:44,070 --> 00:07:47,320
Now it's time to go to work.

41
00:07:55,330 --> 00:07:58,630
You'll make a good first impression.

42
00:08:06,680 --> 00:08:09,470
I love you, Eliot.

43
00:08:14,850 --> 00:08:16,180
Now, shoo.

44
00:08:17,980 --> 00:08:23,610
Eliot Ness, Special Agent
of the Treasury Department.

45
00:08:23,820 --> 00:08:26,320
- Mr Ness.
- Thank you, Chief.

46
00:08:26,530 --> 00:08:29,860
At the request
of the City of Chicago,

47
00:08:30,070 --> 00:08:33,830
the Department of the Treasury
has inaugurated a programme

48
00:08:34,040 --> 00:08:37,580
to deal with the flow of illegal
liquor and the violence it creates.

49
00:08:37,790 --> 00:08:41,580
Mr Ness!
Of what does this programme consist?

50
00:08:41,790 --> 00:08:44,630
I and other agents of the Treasury
will be working

51
00:08:44,840 --> 00:08:46,880
with the Chicago Police...

52
00:08:47,090 --> 00:08:49,300
Isn't it just another
showpiece programme?

53
00:08:49,510 --> 00:08:53,680
- What do you think of prohibition?
- Do you drink, Mr Ness?

54
00:08:53,890 --> 00:08:57,770
- Come on, answer the questions.
- It's not just a showpiece.

55
00:08:57,980 --> 00:09:01,190
And I'll tell you
how I feel about prohibition.

56
00:09:01,400 --> 00:09:02,810
It is the law of the land.

57
00:09:03,020 --> 00:09:05,780
Do you consider yourself
a crusader, is that it?

58
00:09:05,980 --> 00:09:08,320
What qualifications
do you have for the job?

59
00:09:08,530 --> 00:09:10,910
Do you have any political ambitions?

60
00:09:11,110 --> 00:09:13,830
All right, boys,
I think that's enough.

61
00:09:16,240 --> 00:09:19,460
What are your real plans?
What have you got coming up?

62
00:09:19,660 --> 00:09:21,750
You'll have to read about it
in the paper.

63
00:09:21,960 --> 00:09:25,630
- Let me ride along with you.
- No. Can't help you.

64
00:09:25,840 --> 00:09:29,090
Mr Ness, Lieutenant Alderson,
the Flying Squad.

65
00:09:29,300 --> 00:09:32,260
Are you ready to meet the men?

66
00:09:33,640 --> 00:09:35,680
Yes, I am.

67
00:09:45,480 --> 00:09:48,490
I have one more thing to say.

68
00:09:52,280 --> 00:09:55,620
I know that many of you take a drink.

69
00:09:55,830 --> 00:09:59,700
What you've done before today
is not my concern.

70
00:09:59,910 --> 00:10:03,460
But now we must be pure,
and I want you to stop.

71
00:10:04,830 --> 00:10:09,260
It's not a question of whether it's
'a harmless drink'. It may well be.

72
00:10:09,460 --> 00:10:11,050
But it's against the law.

73
00:10:11,260 --> 00:10:15,510
And as we are going to enforce
the law, we must do first by example.

74
00:10:20,310 --> 00:10:22,890
Are there any questions?

75
00:10:24,270 --> 00:10:27,650
Good. The Department
of the Treasury's had

76
00:10:27,860 --> 00:10:29,990
a man undercover here
for some time now.

77
00:10:30,190 --> 00:10:32,240
We've received word
from this informant

78
00:10:32,450 --> 00:10:35,950
that a large shipment of Canadian
whiskey has arrived in Chicago.

79
00:10:36,160 --> 00:10:38,870
So I hope that you have signed on
for some action.

80
00:10:46,920 --> 00:10:51,550
Remember, the liquor cases
are marked with the red maple leaf.

81
00:10:51,760 --> 00:10:55,010
The Treasury Agent is
in a grey suit with a white scarf.

82
00:10:55,220 --> 00:10:59,810
- He is not to be arrested.
- A grey suit and a white scarf.

83
00:11:00,020 --> 00:11:04,390
- That's it. Are your men ready?
- Yes, sir. They are.

84
00:11:11,320 --> 00:11:14,820
- At ease.
- Smoke 'em if you got 'em.

85
00:11:21,080 --> 00:11:23,660
- How are we doin'
- Okay.

86
00:11:29,540 --> 00:11:33,130
- Want part of a sandwich?
- No, thank you, sir.

87
00:11:39,600 --> 00:11:42,310
- You nervous?
- No, sir.

88
00:11:44,310 --> 00:11:48,100
- Been with the unit long?
- A short while.

89
00:11:49,480 --> 00:11:53,190
- I suppose we all want to do well.
- Yes, sir.

90
00:11:59,070 --> 00:12:01,910
A message from my wife.

91
00:12:02,990 --> 00:12:06,410
- You married?
- Yes, sir, I am.

92
00:12:06,620 --> 00:12:09,420
Nice to be married, huh?

93
00:12:26,520 --> 00:12:28,400
Just follow me.

94
00:13:10,440 --> 00:13:13,230
- Oh, God...
- Federal officer. Hands in the air.

95
00:13:13,440 --> 00:13:15,780
Get 'em up. Drop it.

96
00:13:15,980 --> 00:13:18,570
Damn it, I can't , it'll break.

97
00:13:19,650 --> 00:13:22,160
Mr Ness. Look, I was just...

98
00:13:22,370 --> 00:13:24,410
Geez, I'm sorry.

99
00:13:26,410 --> 00:13:30,170
Listen, I can do a lot for you,
what you're tryin' to do.

100
00:13:30,370 --> 00:13:32,580
I get the big scoop,
you make a big splash.

101
00:13:32,790 --> 00:13:37,300
Get some support. What do you say?
Let's be real, let me help you.

102
00:13:37,510 --> 00:13:39,720
Okay. Just shut up.

103
00:14:06,280 --> 00:14:09,120
All right now...
Let's do some good!

104
00:14:23,010 --> 00:14:24,510
Hold it right there!

105
00:14:27,100 --> 00:14:31,770
Federal officer. You're under arrest
for violations of the Volstead Act.

106
00:14:40,650 --> 00:14:43,700
Let's cover the doors!
Don't let anybody out!

107
00:14:45,490 --> 00:14:47,700
Preseuski.

108
00:14:48,790 --> 00:14:51,910
- I'm here with permission.
- Who gave you permission?

109
00:14:52,120 --> 00:14:55,040
- Mr Ness!
- Sorry, let him through here.

110
00:14:56,040 --> 00:14:58,800
Let him through here.

111
00:14:59,920 --> 00:15:03,130
You want to take your picture,
take it now.

112
00:15:04,220 --> 00:15:06,640
- You ready?
- Ready.

113
00:15:32,750 --> 00:15:34,790
Liquor, huh?

114
00:15:37,250 --> 00:15:39,250
Get him out of here.

115
00:15:39,460 --> 00:15:43,550
- Tear the place apart!
- I mean now, get him out!

116
00:15:48,140 --> 00:15:50,720
That means you, too.

117
00:15:55,560 --> 00:15:57,440
Christ!

118
00:17:15,770 --> 00:17:19,480
Now, what do you think you're doing?

119
00:17:19,690 --> 00:17:24,570
You want to throw garbage? Throw it
in the goddamn trash basket.

120
00:17:24,770 --> 00:17:27,990
Don't you have
more important things to do?

121
00:17:28,240 --> 00:17:30,360
Yeah.

122
00:17:30,570 --> 00:17:33,160
But I'm not doing them right now.

123
00:17:34,240 --> 00:17:37,040
Do we understand each other?

124
00:17:40,420 --> 00:17:43,170
Okay, pal, why the Mohaska?

125
00:17:44,590 --> 00:17:48,420
- Why are you packin' the gun?
- I'm a Treasury Officer.

126
00:17:51,380 --> 00:17:53,550
All right.

127
00:17:53,760 --> 00:17:57,470
Just remember
what we talked about now.

128
00:18:01,440 --> 00:18:03,860
Hey... Wait a minute!

129
00:18:04,060 --> 00:18:07,820
What the hell kind of police
do you have in this goddamn citÃ½?

130
00:18:08,030 --> 00:18:10,900
You just turned your back
on an armed man.

131
00:18:11,110 --> 00:18:14,870
- You're a Treasury officer.
- I just told you I was.

132
00:18:15,080 --> 00:18:18,200
Who would claim to be that,
who was not?

133
00:18:24,080 --> 00:18:27,170
What's your name and unit?

134
00:18:30,880 --> 00:18:33,510
It's right here.

135
00:18:34,930 --> 00:18:38,310
You got a beef?
What is it?

136
00:18:40,730 --> 00:18:43,770
How did you know I had a gun?

137
00:18:43,980 --> 00:18:47,770
What do you want,
a free lesson in police work?

138
00:18:50,150 --> 00:18:51,490
No.

139
00:18:54,910 --> 00:18:56,780
Are you okay, pal?

140
00:18:58,580 --> 00:19:01,330
I had a rough day on the job.

141
00:19:02,960 --> 00:19:06,040
- Are you going home now?
- I was about to.

142
00:19:09,000 --> 00:19:13,010
Well, then, you just fulfilled
the first rule of law enforcement.

143
00:19:17,100 --> 00:19:21,060
Make sure when your shift is over
you go home alive.

144
00:19:22,140 --> 00:19:24,390
Here endeth the lesson.

145
00:20:22,540 --> 00:20:27,370
$100,000 for 40 barrels.
Make sure there are no empties.

146
00:20:27,580 --> 00:20:30,670
I'm gonna give you the ledger,
everything is in the book.

147
00:20:30,880 --> 00:20:33,840
55 gallons to the barrel.

148
00:20:47,730 --> 00:20:50,440
<i>- It's Eddie.
- Come in, Eddie.</i>

149
00:21:14,550 --> 00:21:20,220
So, he gets into the snowplough,
and he says, "Let's do some good" .

150
00:21:20,430 --> 00:21:22,850
And then, we bust through...

151
00:22:11,810 --> 00:22:15,440
- Mr Ness?
- Yes?

152
00:22:15,650 --> 00:22:18,990
I came here to thank you.

153
00:22:19,190 --> 00:22:20,610
It was...

154
00:22:20,820 --> 00:22:24,620
..my little girl that got killed
with that bomb.

155
00:22:26,120 --> 00:22:27,950
I'm sorry. Please.

156
00:22:29,620 --> 00:22:32,120
I'm ...l'm so sorry.

157
00:22:33,210 --> 00:22:38,130
You see, it's ...because I know
that you have children, too.

158
00:22:39,210 --> 00:22:44,470
And that this is real for you,
that these men cause us tragedy.

159
00:22:44,680 --> 00:22:48,390
And I know that you will
put a stop to them.

160
00:22:49,470 --> 00:22:51,270
And you do that, now.

161
00:23:48,280 --> 00:23:51,580
- What do you want?
- I'd like to talk to you.

162
00:23:53,830 --> 00:23:55,960
Come in.

163
00:23:59,380 --> 00:24:02,340
I need a small group of men,
handpicked, starting with you.

164
00:24:02,550 --> 00:24:06,510
Ness! I am just a poor beat cop.

165
00:24:07,510 --> 00:24:12,930
<i>- Now, how can I help you?
- Just work with me.</i>

166
00:24:13,140 --> 00:24:16,730
- But why should I, though?
- Because you're a good cop.

167
00:24:18,190 --> 00:24:20,820
- How do you know that?
- You told me.

168
00:24:21,610 --> 00:24:24,030
If I'm such a good cop...

169
00:24:25,320 --> 00:24:28,320
How come I'm walkin' the beat,
then, at my age?

170
00:24:28,530 --> 00:24:30,450
Do you want to tell me?

171
00:24:30,660 --> 00:24:33,540
Well, maybe I'm that
Whore with a Heart of Gold.

172
00:24:33,750 --> 00:24:37,500
Or The One Good Cop in the Bad Town?
Is that what you want to hear?

173
00:24:37,710 --> 00:24:39,710
I didn't ask you, and I don't care!

174
00:24:39,920 --> 00:24:43,670
You want to stay on the beat?
You do that.

175
00:24:43,880 --> 00:24:48,220
If you'd like to come with me,
I need your help.

176
00:24:50,180 --> 00:24:51,890
I'm askin' you for help.

177
00:24:55,980 --> 00:24:59,850
Well...that's the thing you fear,
isn't it?

178
00:25:03,570 --> 00:25:08,860
Mr Ness, I wish I'd met you
ten years and...twenty pounds ago.

179
00:25:09,070 --> 00:25:14,790
But...I just think it got...
more important to me...

180
00:25:15,000 --> 00:25:16,710
..to stay alive.

181
00:25:24,000 --> 00:25:28,010
And that's why I'm walkin' the beat.
Thank you, no.

182
00:25:42,360 --> 00:25:45,980
<i>That's good, Andy. Let's start up
the thing and take a little ride.</i>

183
00:25:46,190 --> 00:25:48,740
<i>I wanna hear
that Stutz Bearcat engine, boy!</i>

184
00:25:48,950 --> 00:25:52,280
<i>- Yeah, let me open the door here.
- Yeah, go ahead.</i>

185
00:25:52,490 --> 00:25:55,910
<i>Whoopsy daisy,
pick up the door there, Andy.</i>

186
00:25:56,120 --> 00:26:00,040
<i>Throw it in the back seat.
Now, let me get the thing started.</i>

187
00:26:00,250 --> 00:26:02,290
<i>Yeah, start it up, Andy.</i>

188
00:26:09,260 --> 00:26:12,340
<i>Holy mackerel, Andy!
Listen to that Bearcat motor!</i>

189
00:26:12,550 --> 00:26:17,270
<i>Yeah, it sounds like the bear
is chasin' that cat all round it!</i>

190
00:26:18,980 --> 00:26:20,980
<i>Andy! She's boilin' over!</i>

191
00:26:32,030 --> 00:26:34,950
- Mr Ness?
- Yes.

192
00:26:35,160 --> 00:26:37,580
Oscar Wallace.

193
00:26:39,410 --> 00:26:42,500
I've been assigned here
by the Washington Bureau.

194
00:26:42,710 --> 00:26:44,960
- Really?
- Yes.

195
00:26:45,170 --> 00:26:49,880
Well, I'm glad to have you here,
Mr Wallace. Would you excuse me?

196
00:26:50,970 --> 00:26:53,800
We are a little in the dark here,
but any ideas you may have...

197
00:26:54,010 --> 00:26:55,970
Well, actually, yes, sir, I do.

198
00:26:56,180 --> 00:27:00,060
And the one I want to try first...
is this.

199
00:27:03,650 --> 00:27:07,730
He has not filed a return since 1926.

200
00:27:09,280 --> 00:27:12,950
- A return...?
- An income tax return.

201
00:27:14,450 --> 00:27:15,950
- Income tax.
- Yes, sir.

202
00:27:16,160 --> 00:27:20,580
- What do you do at the Bureau?
- Oh, I'm an accountant.

203
00:27:21,660 --> 00:27:25,790
- An accountant?
- Yes, and the Bureau sent me here...

204
00:27:26,880 --> 00:27:29,090
Would you excuse me?

205
00:27:32,420 --> 00:27:34,840
Please.

206
00:28:00,410 --> 00:28:02,870
Okay. Let's go.

207
00:28:03,080 --> 00:28:07,000
- Where are we going?
- These walls have ears.

208
00:28:09,750 --> 00:28:13,920
You said you wanted to know
how to get Capone.

209
00:28:16,260 --> 00:28:20,640
Do you really want to get him?
You see what I'm saying?

210
00:28:20,850 --> 00:28:25,440
- What are you prepared to do?
- Everything within the law.

211
00:28:25,640 --> 00:28:28,610
And then what are you
prepared to do?

212
00:28:28,810 --> 00:28:31,190
If you open the ball
on these people,

213
00:28:31,400 --> 00:28:33,940
you must be prepared
to go all the way.

214
00:28:34,150 --> 00:28:37,320
Because they won't give up the fight
until one of you is dead.

215
00:28:37,530 --> 00:28:39,620
I want to get Capone.
I don't know how.

216
00:28:39,820 --> 00:28:44,700
Here's how you get Capone:
he pulls a knife, you pull a gun.

217
00:28:44,910 --> 00:28:47,670
He sends one of yours to hospital,
you send one of his to the morgue!

218
00:28:47,870 --> 00:28:51,500
That's the Chicago way!
And that's how you get Capone.

219
00:28:53,800 --> 00:28:57,010
Now, do you want to do that?

220
00:28:57,220 --> 00:28:59,930
Are you ready to do that?

221
00:29:01,550 --> 00:29:05,560
I'm making you a deal.
Do you want this deal?

222
00:29:06,600 --> 00:29:09,020
I have sworn to put this man away,

223
00:29:09,230 --> 00:29:14,400
with any and all legal means
at my disposal, and I will do so.

224
00:29:22,240 --> 00:29:25,580
Well, the Lord hates a coward.

225
00:29:32,750 --> 00:29:35,960
Do you know what a blood oath is,
Mr Ness?

226
00:29:36,170 --> 00:29:39,130
- Yes.
- Good. 'Cause you just took one.

227
00:29:41,180 --> 00:29:44,390
How do you think Capone knew
about your raid the other night?

228
00:29:44,600 --> 00:29:48,230
- Somebody on the cops told him.
- Right. Welcome to Chicago.

229
00:29:48,440 --> 00:29:51,900
This town stinks
like a whorehouse at low tide.

230
00:29:52,110 --> 00:29:56,610
First, who can you trust?
Nobody. The cops, nobody.

231
00:29:56,820 --> 00:30:01,570
- 'Cause nobody wants you here.
- Then why are you helping me?

232
00:30:01,780 --> 00:30:04,780
Because I swore to uphold the law.

233
00:30:04,990 --> 00:30:07,830
And if you believe that,
I'll tell you another.

234
00:30:08,040 --> 00:30:12,290
- Now, who can you trust?
- I can trust nobody.

235
00:30:12,500 --> 00:30:16,590
- That's the sorry truth.
- Then, where are we gonna get help?

